    <h2 id="why-iodine">Why Iodine Deficiency Is Making a Comeback in America</h2>

    <p>Iodine deficiency was once considered a solved problem in the United States. The introduction of iodized salt in 1924 virtually eliminated goiter and cretinism within a generation. But over the past three decades, American iodine intake has declined by more than 50%. The culprit is not a single dietary change but a convergence of trends: the widespread adoption of non-iodized specialty salts (sea salt, Himalayan pink salt, kosher salt), the movement toward lower sodium diets, the decline of dairy consumption, and the rise of processed foods that use non-iodized salt in manufacturing.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">50%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">decline in median urinary iodine concentration among US adults since the 1970s, according to NHANES data. While overt deficiency remains uncommon, subclinical insufficiency is increasingly prevalent — particularly among pregnant women, where one-third now have iodine levels below the WHO sufficiency threshold.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The thyroid gland is a butterfly-shaped organ at the base of your neck that produces T3 and T4 — hormones that regulate the metabolic rate of virtually every cell in your body. These hormones control how fast your heart beats, how efficiently you burn calories, how well you think, and even your body temperature. Without iodine, the thyroid simply cannot manufacture these hormones. The result is hypothyroidism: fatigue, weight gain, brain fog, cold intolerance, dry skin, hair loss, and depression. During pregnancy, even mild iodine insufficiency can impair fetal brain development — making iodine supplementation particularly critical for women of childbearing age.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
