      <cite>Thyroid, 2020; American Thyroid Association guidelines</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Potassium Iodide vs. Kelp: Precision vs. Whole-Food</h3>

    <p>Iodine supplements come in two primary forms. Potassium iodide (KI) is a synthetic salt that delivers a precise, consistent iodine dose per serving — the same form used in iodized table salt and clinical studies. Kelp-sourced iodine is derived from marine seaweed and is considered a whole-food, natural source. While kelp provides trace minerals alongside iodine, its iodine content is inherently variable. A 2014 analysis in <em>Thyroid</em> tested 25 kelp supplements and found that actual iodine content ranged from 33% to 1,032% of the labeled amount. This variability makes precise dosing with kelp supplements challenging. Our top recommendations prioritize dosing accuracy, especially for a mineral where both deficiency and excess can harm the thyroid.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Label reading tip:</strong> Look for the iodine source: "potassium iodide" provides the most precise dosing. "Kelp" or "Ascophyllum nodosum" indicates a natural source with potentially variable iodine content. For thyroid conditions, potassium iodide is preferred. Also check whether selenium is included — the iodine + selenium combination provides more comprehensive thyroid support.</p>
    </div>

