    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Iodine Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does iodine do for the thyroid?</summary>
      <p>Iodine is the essential raw material for thyroid hormones T3 and T4, which regulate metabolism, heart rate, body temperature, and brain function. Without iodine, the thyroid cannot produce these hormones.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much iodine do I need daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA is 150mcg for adults, 220mcg during pregnancy, and 290mcg during lactation. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 1,100mcg. Median US intake has declined over 50% since the 1970s.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between potassium iodide and kelp-sourced iodine?</summary>
      <p>Potassium iodide provides precise, consistent dosing. Kelp provides whole-food iodine with trace minerals but can vary in iodine content. For dosing accuracy, potassium iodide is preferred.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can too much iodine hurt my thyroid?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Excessive iodine can cause both hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism, particularly in individuals with pre-existing thyroid conditions. Stay near the RDA (150mcg) unless directed otherwise by an endocrinologist.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Who is most at risk for iodine deficiency?</summary>
      <p>Pregnant and lactating women, people using non-iodized salt, vegans, vegetarians, individuals with fat malabsorption, and those on restrictive diets face the highest risk.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take iodine with selenium?</summary>
      <p>Yes — selenium activates the enzyme that converts T4 to active T3 and protects the thyroid from oxidative damage. The iodine + selenium combination provides more comprehensive thyroid support.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is iodine safe during pregnancy?</summary>
      <p>Iodine is essential during pregnancy. The ATA recommends 150mcg supplemental iodine daily for pregnant women. About 50% of US prenatal vitamins do not include iodine. Consult your OB/GYN.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What foods are high in iodine?</summary>
      <p>Seaweed, iodized salt, cod, dairy products, shrimp, eggs, and tuna are the richest sources. Non-iodized salts (sea salt, Himalayan, kosher) contain negligible iodine.</p>
    </details>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> Individuals with thyroid conditions (Hashimoto's thyroiditis, Graves' disease, thyroid nodules) should consult an endocrinologist before taking iodine supplements. Excess iodine can worsen these conditions. If you take thyroid medication (levothyroxine), iodine supplementation may require dose adjustments.</p>
    </div>

